 1186","Goosnargh, Lancashire, England":"Goosnargh, Lancashire, England","Catterall, Lancashire, England":"Catterall, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert FitzBernard de Goosnargh was born about 1160, in Goosnargh, Lancashire, England, his father, Bernard de Goosnargh, was 32 and his mother, Miss FitzOrm, was 19. He had at least 1 son and 3 daughters with Hawise. He died in 1206, in Catterall, Lancashire, England, at the age of 47."},"et":{"about 1160–1206":"umbes 1160–1206","1160–1206":"1160–1206","1164–Female":"1164–Surnud","1177–Female":"1177–Surnud","1180–Female":"1180–Surnud","1186–Male":"1186–Surnud","–1219":"–1219","1130–1190":"1130–1190","1143–Female":"1143–Surnud","1190":"1190","about 1160":"umbes 1160","about 1190":"umbes 1190","about 1180":"umbes 1180","ABT 1158":"umbes 1158","1143":"1143","1186":"1186","1164":"1164","1130":"1130","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","1206":"1206","1177":"1177","from 1189 to 1199":"1189 kuni 1199","about 1177":"umbes 11